Observation Details: ***MEGA - first record for Florida; one foraged with swallows (60 Tree, 2 Bank, 1 N. Rough-winged) over low prairie just north of coastal prairie trail west of C loop at Flamingo campground.  Glen Davis first spotted this awesome bird as it zipped past us heading east. We then had extended, excellent views of it in comparison to Tree Swallows. The bird appeared slim and flew with rapid wingbeats, gliding on slightly bowed wings. It had a mostly white rump divided into two white rump spots by a dark longitudinal bar, and a white facial crescent that wrapped around and above the eye. The head had a bronzy sheen, and the back and lesser coverts had a green sheen. The bird was also giving sizzling 'zap' calls, very different from the mellow "chee" notes of Tree Swallows. The bird was still present when we left, and the flock seemed to be staying in the area, though Larry Manfredi did not see it during a vigil later in the day. Observation Details: The mixed flock of swallows was working over the N end of the N cove when we approached the area.  Periodically, they would take turns landing in scrub trees on the eastern hillside above the cove.  In several photos that Keith took, all three swallow species seen this day were perched at the same time.  In flight, the white love handles on the Violet-green helped differentiate them from the Tree Swallows.  Perched, it was easy to see the white on the cheek extend into the Violet-green’s eye area, while remaining below the eye on the Tree Swallow.  The less flashy Northern Rough-winged was still fun to see.  These are minimum counts on all swallow species.

Observation Details: At least two immatures in swallow house. One notably smaller (likely a female) than the other though both taking turns at the orifice. Parent feeding continues but not as actively as day prior this a.m.. At 11:57 a.m. I noted the female go in the Box for a lengthy period of time, one of the immature had then poked its head out of the box 'then' the female left. This was the longest stay I've seen possibly in the entire duration since birth. She was in there a good 15 to 20 seconds. Moments after the male went 'inside' the swallow box for the first time, delivered food then left.  At 2:01 p.m. the male entered the Box again and did a turn around inside the swallow box. this is the first I've seen of the male's behavior beginning today. ***MEGA - first record for Florida; one foraged with swallows (60 Tree, 2 Bank, 1 N. Rough-winged) over low prairie just north of coastal prairie trail west of C loop at Flamingo campground.  Glen Davis first spotted this awesome bird as it zipped past us heading east. We then had extended, excellent views of it in comparison to Tree Swallows. The bird appeared slim and flew with rapid wingbeats, gliding on slightly bowed wings. It had a mostly white rump divided into two white rump spots by a dark longitudinal bar, and a white facial crescent that wrapped around and above the eye. The head had a bronzy sheen, and the back and lesser coverts had a green sheen. The bird was also giving sizzling 'zap' calls, very different from the mellow "chee" notes of Tree Swallows. The bird was still present when we left, and the flock seemed to be staying in the area, though Larry Manfredi did not see it during a vigil later in the day. This is a second active Violet-Green Swallow cavity nest discovered shortly before sunset on June 27, 2021. Two attending adults and undetermined number of young inside the cavity nest. The begging chirps of the young were readily audible but the hatchlings themselves were not visible. The nest cavity tree was a large Western Sycamore which was growing immediately adjacent to the bone-dry Penitencia Creek itself. The cavity height was approximately 40 feet above ground level. My photos are slightly underexposed since this nest was discovered just before sunset and the light was fading quickly.

Locality: Sand Island CG & Bluff Road Bridge

Observation Details: At least 300 swallows perched on this wire during the rain storm. Poor light, and hard to get photo’s in such heavy rain, but it was interesting to see that the VG Swallows had a way of tilting their heads skyward and closing their eyes — almost appearing to enjoy the shower. In contrast to the cliff swallows who appeared to just sit there with their grumpy faces on. All species of swallows on the wire seemed chilled and did a lot of shaking - probably just shaking the water off. It rained really hard for at least 15 minutes. One final note, I am always amazed at how long the primary extension is on VG’s compared to all other swallows.

It was approximately the same size as the Northern Rough-winged Swallows.  It was green on the back and head, white underneath and on the face and around the eyes, and with tones of purple and violet on the rump. These details are based on my photos since I don't remember this specific bird as I was taking photos.    I didn't recognize that the swallow was unusual until later in the morning as I was viewing all of my photos at the Preserve on a large screen.

Observation Details: (Behavioral notes included with history). A friend and I built this swallow house to spec with the opening at 1.5" tight enough so a House Sparrow or European Starling cant make entrance on 4-5-19. The house was painted and installed on 4-6-19 to deter the swallows from going into our eves as they did in 2018 and the area screened off.  However, from approximately 3-30-19 (their first arrival date) they did tend to hang around the eves seemingly a bit confused thus showing they returned to the same successful breeding location.  The philosophy worked on the Swallow House as its mounted just below the eves where they gained entrance last year.  The pair began checking out the house through 4-30-19 and opted only once to peek inside.  The female claimed ownership on May 1, 2019 as in my report that day with a lone image.  The Violet-green Swallow pair has adopted well and roughly two weeks ago new bedding was brought in as we noted large feathers during that period scattered around the deck. Currently, from 8:30pm this evening, the Violet-green Swallow female has been making 3 to 4 trips to tend the nest vs. male's 1 trip. She returns every 3 to 7 minutes and tends for 1 to 2 minutes.  Observed until approx. 9pm (I did take a cell video of both leaving the nest at the same time).  At times they are both in the box simultaneously but its about 15 seconds.  When the male makes entrance solo, he stays under one minute.  Images are below

Observation Details: Odd to see this here.  Was flying around over the park.

I was standing near the end of the road by Lake Jackson with Marcie and Parker scanning the Tree Swallows, which kept flying overhead in small waves. I was looking for anything different, and in particular was checking for Cave.  I first noticed this bird when it flew in from the NW and came nearly directly overhead. I was scanning with the naked eye at this point, and noticed that the general impression of this one stood out from the others, in that it was a bit smaller, with a shorter tail and a slightly different flight style (more fluttery and less strong and sturdy than TRSW). The bird had all white underparts and brownish-greenish upperparts, somewhat similar to a female or juvenile Tree. The bird banked, revealing sizable white patches on either side of the rump, and circled around briefly before continuing SSE. Once the bird had vanished to the south, I reviewed my photos on the back of my camera and saw that the bird had a facial pattern typical of VGSW, with white extending over the eye and lacking a sharply contrasting cheek patch typical of TRSW. A few minutes later I saw what I believe to be the same bird heading back north, but the bird was fairly distant to the east. Observation in my binoculars again seemed to reveal a facial and rump pattern consistent with VGSW, with a GISS different from TRSW.   I believe this is a hatch-year bird in its performative molt. Marks that suggest hatch-year are the dusky feathers around the face, brownish-greenish shoulder spur, and dullish upperparts. The bird shows some white over the eye, which is typical for hatch-year birds in late fall, and white rump patches that are much more extensive than the white crescents sometimes seen on Tree Swallow. This bird is missing some undertail coverts, which means that the undertail coverts do not reach the tip of the tail, as is typical of adults. This state of molt appears typical, however, for hatch year birds in late fall.

Two immatures poked their heads out for the first time at 18:15 hrs, Non stop chick chatter.  Soon after Mother hauled out what appeared to be a deceased immature, have image attached. Observation Details: (Behavioral notes included with history). A friend and I built this swallow house to spec with the opening at 1.5" tight enough so a House Sparrow or European Starling cant make entrance on 4-5-19. The house was painted and installed on 4-6-19 to deter the swallows from going into our eves as they did in 2018 and the area screened off.  However, from approximately 3-30-19 (their first arrival date) they did tend to hang around the eves seemingly a bit confused thus showing they returned to the same successful breeding location.  The philosophy worked on the Swallow House as its mounted just below the eves where they gained entrance last year.  The pair began checking out the house through 4-30-19 and opted only once to peek inside.  The female claimed ownership on May 1, 2019 as in my report that day with a lone image.  The Violet-green Swallow pair has adopted well and roughly two weeks ago new bedding was brought in as we noted large feathers during that period scattered around the deck. Currently, from 8:30pm this evening, the Violet-green Swallow female has been making 3 to 4 trips to tend the nest vs. male's 1 trip. She returns every 3 to 7 minutes and tends for 1 to 2 minutes.  Observed until approx. 9pm (I did take a cell video of both leaving the nest at the same time).  At times they are both in the box simultaneously but its about 15 seconds.  When the male makes entrance solo, he stays under one minute.  Images are below

I was standing near the end of the road by Lake Jackson with Marcie and Parker scanning the Tree Swallows, which kept flying overhead in small waves. I was looking for anything different, and in particular was checking for Cave.  I first noticed this bird when it flew in from the NW and came nearly directly overhead. I was scanning with the naked eye at this point, and noticed that the general impression of this one stood out from the others, in that it was a bit smaller, with a shorter tail and a slightly different flight style (more fluttery and less strong and sturdy than TRSW). The bird had all white underparts and brownish-greenish upperparts, somewhat similar to a female or juvenile Tree. The bird banked, revealing sizable white patches on either side of the rump, and circled around briefly before continuing SSE. Once the bird had vanished to the south, I reviewed my photos on the back of my camera and saw that the bird had a facial pattern typical of VGSW, with white extending over the eye and lacking a sharply contrasting cheek patch typical of TRSW. A few minutes later I saw what I believe to be the same bird heading back north, but the bird was fairly distant to the east. Observation in my binoculars again seemed to reveal a facial and rump pattern consistent with VGSW, with a GISS different from TRSW.   I believe this is a hatch-year bird in its performative molt. Marks that suggest hatch-year are the dusky feathers around the face, brownish-greenish shoulder spur, and dullish upperparts. The bird shows some white over the eye, which is typical for hatch-year birds in late fall, and white rump patches that are much more extensive than the white crescents sometimes seen on Tree Swallow. This bird is missing some undertail coverts, which means that the undertail coverts do not reach the tip of the tail, as is typical of adults. This state of molt appears typical, however, for hatch year birds in late fall.

Media notes: After picking this bird up to move it out of harms way, this bird flew from my hand. Note the molt limits in the primaries and secondaries.
Observation Details: One time count of those over the lake, they were flying everywhere so this is extremely conservative.  They appeared to be flying slower than usual. Also observed at least a dozen carcasses floating in the pond, picked up seven or eight from ground in parking lot to move them out of harms way. They seem tired, perhaps starving & dehydrated. All but one flew from my hand or flew soon after being placed on the ground in a safe place. One died shortly after being place on the ground. The latter was first found on the ground face away from wind, and was tipping forward due to wind gust, see first photo. Adults and HY. Many observed up close and handled appear to be in molt, or migrating with retained older outer primaries.
